-- China, India, Malaysia, Thailand, Singapore: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview
-- David Yong
-- 2010-07-20T22:53:24Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-20/china-india-malaysia-thailand-singapore-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshito Sengoku will hold a
media briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo. The Cabinet Office will
publish its monthly economic report after a meeting during the
day.  
 The Bank of Japan will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo the
minutes of its June 14-15 policy board meeting. Deputy Governor
Hirohide Yamaguchi will speak at a business meeting at 10:30 a.m.
in Toyama City. He will also have a press briefing at 2:30 p.m.  
 The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond due in June
2020 was 1.09 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker. Financial markets were
closed yesterday for a public holiday.  
 The yen traded at 87.38 per dollar at 7:42 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: The finance ministry will sell at least 28 billion
yuan ($4.1 billion) of seven-year bonds today. The securities
may yield 2.75 percent, according to median estimate in a
Bloomberg News survey. The paper yielded 2.83 percent at the
previous sale on May 26.  
 The yield on the 2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was
2.59 percent. The yuan was at 6.778 per dollar.  
 India: The government will today sell 20 billion rupees
($424 million) of 91-day bills and 15 billion rupees of 182-day
bills.  
 The yield on the 7.8 percent note due in May 2020 was 7.665
percent. The rupee was at 47.3637 per dollar.  
 Malaysia: The central bank will sell 2 billion ringgit
($623 million) each of notes maturing in 58 and 91 days. It will
also sell 1 billion ringgit of 63-day notes based on Shariah
principles.  
 Consumer prices probably rose 1.7 percent in June from a
year earlier, versus 1.6 percent in May, according to the median
forecast in a Bloomberg survey. The statistics department will
release the data at 5 p.m. in Kuala Lumpur.  
 The yield on the 3.835 percent debt maturing in August 2015
was 3.36 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit was
at 3.22 per dollar.  
 Philippines: The government may publish its June budget
balance as early as today, Finance Secretary Cesar Purisima said.
The shortfall likely exceeded the estimate of 178.5 billion
pesos ($3.8 billion) for the first half, Budget Secretary
Florencio Abad said yesterday.  
 The yield on the 7.75 percent debt due February 2020 was
7.725 percent. The peso was at 46.428 per dollar.  
 Singapore: Inflation probably accelerated 3.5 percent in
June from a year earlier, according to a Bloomberg News survey
before a government report on July 23. Prices rose 3.2 percent
in May.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due in September 2020
was 2.24 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3740 per
dollar.  
 Taiwan: The government will sell NT$35 billion ($1.09
billion) of 91-day treasury bills on July 23. Export orders
climbed 22.48 percent in June from a year earlier, after gaining
34.03 percent in May, the statistics bureau said after the close
of local trading yesterday.  
 Thailand: The government will today auction 15 billion baht
($465 million) of 2019 bonds and 9 billion baht of floating-rate
notes due in 2014. They yielded 3.399 percent and 1.519 percent
respectively at the previous sale on May 26.  
 Exports increased 34.5 percent in June from a year earlier
after rising 42.1 percent in May, a government report to be
issued at 10 a.m. in Bangkok today may show, according to the
median estimate in a Bloomberg survey. The yield on the 3.625
percent note due in May 2015 was 2.97 percent. The baht was at
32.30 per dollar.  
